# Site Current Problem Suggested 1 cli/src/lib.rs:875 (do_trace) Err(e) => format!("Error: {}
", e.message) No context: which command failed? Just "Error: foo". format!("Error: .trace: {}
", e.message) 2 cli/src/lib.rs:561 format!("Unknown command: {trimmed}
") Doesn't suggest .help for discovery. User has no next step. format!("Unknown command: {trimmed}
Run .help to list available commands.
") 3 cli/src/lib.rs:984 (.read) format!("Error: cannot open {arg}: {e}
") OK but {e} is std::io::Error debug, e.g. "No such file or directory (os error 2)" — verbose. Surface the underlying kind() and skip the (os error 2) postfix; .read FILE: file not found is enough. 4 cli/src/lib.rs:1057 format!("Bad flag: {arg} (expected --key=value)
") Doesn't say WHICH command was being .loaded; user invoking .load foo.wasm --trustt=stored (typo) sees just "Bad flag: --trustt=stored". format!(".load: bad flag {arg} (expected --key=value, e.g. --trust=stored)
") 5 cli/src/lib.rs:1162,1202,1246,1251 (.load) format!("Error describing {path}: {} (code {})
", e.message, e.code) The "(code N)" sqlite code is jargon; users don't know what code 1 means. Drop the parenthetical OR translate well-known codes to names. format!("Error: .load {path}: {} [SQLITE_ERROR]
", e.message) for code=1, etc. Pattern: errors describe the failure but not the user's invocation. A consistent prefix (.<command> <arg>:) would fix 60% of the 50+ error sites.
